Emperor Shah Jahan, created many monuments and forts in this city during their ruling period, and all these places still manage to attract lakhs of tourists from all over the world because of their beautiful architecture. Many visitors come to this city to learn riveting historical facts about Agra and Fatehpur Sikri and admire the rich & beautiful Mughal architecture. This article provides a complete list of tourist places and attractions that visitors must visit and include in their list while planning a trip to Agra. 1. Radha Soami Samadhi When having a trip to Agra, the Radha Soami Samadhi, an ornate building and one of the most iconic destinations of this city, cannot be missed. The people who have faith in Radha Soami and worship their name, count it as one of the most prestigious places of worship. The main characterization of this tourist place is the surrounding pillars and a large dome in the centre of the building. The founder of the Radha Soami faith, Huzur Swamiji Maharaj, started the construction of this temple, and it is his mausoleum. The interesting fact about Radha Soami Samadhi is that its consecution began in 1904 and continued for a century. This place is located at the Soami Bagh of Poiya Ghat Rd of the city. Timings for visiting the place- Weekdays: 10:00 AM - 5:00 PM Weekend: 10:00 AM - 5:00 PM 2. Mariam-Uz-Zamani Tomb Built by Jahangir, Mariam-Uz-Zamani Tomb is the mausoleum of Jodha Bai, who was the Hindu wife of the emperor Akbar, and it is listed among one of the most popular tourist places in Agra. The Hindu wife of emperor Akbar was known by a lot of names in history books, and Mariam-Uz-Zamani is one of her most popular names. Jahangir built this tomb as the mausoleum in fond memory of his loving mother, and it is located on the west side of Akbar's tomb. Positioned at Mathura Road near Pathwari Mandir of Mahadev Pur, this tomb is surrounded by lavish Mughal gardens and constructed with red sandstone. Timings for visiting the place- Weekdays: 10:00 AM - 6:00 PM Weekend: 10:00 AM - 7:00 PM 3. Nagina Masjid Nagina Masjid is one of the magnificent attractions to explore in Agra, and Shah Jahan built this Masjid during 1631-1640 AD for the royal ladies. Located in Agra Fort, Rakabanj, Agra, it is a private mosque that was constructed using white marble with decent decoration and astute architecture. Also, this beautiful mosque is characterized by wonderful domes and praiseworthy arches. Timings for visiting the place- 6:00 am to 6:00 pm 4. Diwan-I-Khas Located in Musamman Burj, SH 62, Agra Fort, Rakabganj, Agra, UP, Diwan-I-Khas is another attraction to explore in the city that was built by Shah Jahan in 1635. It is a private section where Shah Jahan met with important and special guests such as kings, nobles, and ambassadors and was also known as The Iwan-I-Khas. It is placed behind Macchi Bhawan. The popular Takht-I-Taus (Peacock Throne) was kept here before it was relocated to Red Fort in Delhi. One can spot Persian inscriptions within the black stones in the hall. Timings for visiting the place- 9:00 am to 5:00 pm. 5. Khas Mahal As the name implies, Khas Mahal was a site erected by the king for his daughters Jahanara and Roshnara and was placed at Agra Fort, Rakabganj, Agra. The ceilings of the mahal are heavily embellished, and wall niches are a perfect treat to one's eyes. In addition, Khas Mahal is edged by Anguri Bagh on one side and Yamuna River on another. One must wander around the site and soak in the magnificent architectonics and captivating views. Timings for visiting the place- 6:00 am to 6:00 pm 6. Diwan-I-Aam As the name says, Diwan-I-Aam used to be the site where public gatherings and general meetings were conducted. Shah Jahan built this site during 1631-40, and it was a place where he used to hear the complaints of common people. The huge hall was originally erected in red sandstone and is partitioned into three sections. The king's throne was separated from the attendants using golden railing in the forepart and silver on the remaining three sites. The pomp where the king addressed the listeners was known as Jharokha Darshan. Timings for visiting the place- 6:00 am to 6:00 pm 7. Machhi Bhawan Located in Agra Fort, Rakabganj, Agra is a site built by Shah Jahan and is placed opposite to Diwan-I-Aam. It is a double-storeyed complex flanked by a lush garden and is characterized by domed galleries. It was embellished with fountains and marble tanks where silver and gold fishes were kept, and this is a reason it was also named Machi Bhawan. This site was Shah Jahan's golden throne that allowed him to have a complete view of the court. Timings for visiting the place- 6:00 am to 6:00 pm 8. Anguri Bagh Anguri Bagh is among the tourist attractions in Agra that is placed on the premises of Agra Fort and was erected by Shah Jahan. The luxuriant gardens were built in 1637 so that in the evening, the emperor could take a leisure walk in the garden. The garden is made in Charbagh style, depicted by four partitions and complex geometrical patterns. The juiciest grapes in those times used to grow in this garden were brought into use for making wine for the king. Timings for visiting the place- 6:00 am to 7:30 pm 9. Akbar's Tomb Located in the great area of the Sikandra region of Agra, Akbar's tomb is the place where the immortal remains of the great emperor Akbar are placed, and this tomb was built-in 1605-1613. Akbar himself ordered the construction of the tomb, and its construction began when he was alive. Even though Aurangzeb's army looted all the jewels, silver, gold and other precious metals and items from the Akbar's tomb during Aurangzeb's reign, this place is still counted among the most beautiful tourist places in Agra. There is one southern way in the tomb, which leads to a huge garden (which is constructed in Charbagh style), and one can enter this tomb through this way. Timings for visiting the place- 6:00 am to 6:00 pm 10. Chini ka Rauza If o